<p>I have this bit of code:</p>  <pre><code>{% for i in list %} &lt;button&gt;{{i}}&lt;/button&gt; {% endfor %} </code></pre>  <p>How do I redirect to a new page and pass it value of <code>i</code> as a context, so that it will be like this:</p>  <pre><code>&lt;h3&gt; You chose {{i}} &lt;/h3&gt; </code></pre>  <p>It doesn't have to be a button, in fact I'd prefer if it could be <code>&lt;span&gt;</code> with sort of the same functionality as in AngularJS <code>ng-click</code> </p>  <p>Do I need to send a request with button click and then handle it in <code>views.py</code>? Can I do this without a form? I would prefer if it just redirected me to <code>.../page?i='whatever'</code> I can do it with </p>  <p><code>&lt;span&gt;&lt;a href=".../page?i={{i}}"&gt;Click&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt;</code></p>  <p>But what's the preferred Django way of doing it?</p>